segments.text: Kruger and all.
I will, Marshall Robinette?
Oh, yeah.
In fact, they were in a special class.
The ones that were taking science were in a special algebra class.
And that I happened to be in, I shouldn't have been in it really, but after laying out of school two years, when I looked at that second
the year algebra that I was supposed to be going into, I discovered I didn't have a clue.
So I dropped English and took first year algebra.
And later on to my ultimate disgrace, the next summer I took a correspondence course in English from the University of Texas.
So I had three credit hours that I made.
Because you know how easy the UT courses are.
So you have at least some lame Longhorn background.
I had three hours at the University of Texas.
But I was in this housing class, and we had a, I can't think of his name, an instructor that was absolutely outstanding.
He could make anybody see it.
And we had a bunch of these football players.
in there that were taking science.

And I was in that class and it was, after getting oriented a couple weeks, it was really a brutish thing for me because I'd taken two years out of high school and as a coach, so I had a lot of fun helping these guys through that course.
Let's see, help me with nicknames for various food items in the dining hall.
Kush, butter, milk, tea.
Ketchup.
That's blood.
Milk was cow, wasn't it?
Yeah.
Bread was veal?
Yeah.
I'll think of some of those and go along.
All right.
Try to recall and share with me some of the pranks, the jokes, the good bull that you knew about, whether you were involved or not, that you knew.
Well, I think I can tell you the ultimate practical joke.
Great.
That was put on the campus when I was in my senior year.
The Baltimore women in training.
I think it was a junior.
I got a hold of one of the...
makeup on this that you'd see in some of the movies, like Frankenstein and that type of stuff.
Big teeth hanging out, grotesque eyes, the whole thing was a real trouble mask.
And he was holding one of the
infantry company.
This is where the, uh, the infantry real body.
And he said, Lester, he said, boy, this guy can scare the wits out of anybody, anybody.
And, uh, uh, he said, uh, if you, he said, you know, you haven't passed Keeley up to any of that, that, that engineers.
He said, I'll, I'll get him to come over there.
He said, I'd like to come along myself.
Uh, and
If after everybody's asleep, if you let him in the room on the day, you'll have more fun.
So I went to let his young break and this guy came over and I mean, he was something else.
And he could fix it when he's sober.
And he had a gate that says,
trouble and he'd wash the clothes even worse, you know.
And it looked like he was a maniac, which he actually did.
And so I'd go in, let him in.
His walk-in room would snap on blank, you see.
And sometimes I'd wait for him to get in that room, and sometimes I wouldn't, you see.
But if not, he'd go and shake the bed, you see.
And there he'd be.
He'd wake up and look into his face and you'd just think most of them would bolt past him and down the hall.
Didn't even notice us laughing there in the hall and get out of the dormitory.
They had one friend named Phil Potts.
Phil was a good steward and a senior didn't have to turn the lights off.
So Phil was doing some work he studied.
So finally, I turned to meet on Phil while he was at his desk.
He went over and kind of leaned over.
Phil looked at me, and I went, wow, we walked in behind that.
And I guarantee you, Phil had goosebumps on his leg.
Had a little part of the eighth of an inch high, and some little goosebumps on top of those.
And he bolted.
He covered, he was on the third stoop and he was down on the ground floor so fast you couldn't even believe it.
But we did this for two, three hours.
I've never participated in a practical joke in such effect.
And no harm done to anybody.
Nobody did good, nobody.
It's funny, I thought, and he had only two occasions somebody attacked him.
Just got to fight and just go after them.
But all these guys, all they wanted was running room.
Get out of there.
Did you and your buddies as fish ever play any jokes on a sophomore?
Can you think of any retaliation?
A little sabotage.
Primarily things like short shooting and stuff like that.
So we'd make it there.
And of course, you'd...
You never short sheet by who you were making them.
But you could short sheet somebody.
I'll mislead things for them, hide things for them.
Did y'all ever do any drown outs of sophomores?
Toward the end of the year, we tried that.
That got us in a big bunch of trouble.
Then we had, at the end of the year, we had a big beer, traditionally they'd come in these years, and a big beer bust at a little lake, actually a pond that was
all maybe four or five feet deep and muddy and all.
And we'd get in there and I'd try to see if we could drown the sophomores.
This went on until my senior year, Colonel Watson, agreed that there wouldn't be any of those things occur.
uh, uh, E Company, uh, which was commanded by, uh, Charlie McDonnell, uh, McDaniels, who was a real good friend of mine since, since deceased, uh, had a feast day.
And uh, Colonel Watson was just absolutely out of his mind.
He was just really with it.
And he called everybody in, including me.
And if anybody's connected with this, I'm going to break them.
So we were all supposed to be able to connect ranks and have a chance to go in service.
And so the order.
for no fish steaks, you see.
Instead of being rooted, to me, as regimental commander, I was only posted in the company commander's office, and I never did a company.
So I'm reminded, Colonel Watson, that if you, and neither did the battalion commanders.
that if he was dealing directly with these company commanders, that he'd put us out of the chain of command.
Well, that made him get mad at him.
But, so I had developed a friendship with the dean of engineering, and we'd get real close to him.
So I hustled off to talk to Gabriel Preston about the situation.
I said, you know, the colonel just needs somebody to talk to.
He said he's about to bust about half the engineer officers.
And I don't know how to give him that, but he got it done.
And I know that at this big meeting, the dining room, he took his capitol board home and threw it on the floor.
And everybody else got off that roof except for me.
I think finally it made that Charlie had to do
Now this beer bust, where was that?
Where was it physically?
Where was it?
West of the tracks?
Somewhere off of Highway 6, east of the campus.
Northeast of the campus.
Southeast of the campus, yes.
And this was day or night?
This was daytime.
Day, okay.
And so your outfit would be there?
Yeah.
I participated in the
when I was a freshman or sophomore.
The juniors and seniors didn't care for that.
No dates.
Now after that, then the freshmen took the stripes off and they were human beings again.
Now this was primarily beer, was there food?
Yeah, some food.
Nobody else except the outfit?
No girls, no parents?
There might be some juniors and seniors kind of observing.
Would there be other outfits having parties at different places, different times?
Yeah.
It was a pretty common thing to have a fish day.
Do you remember any other pranks played on sophomores or seniors?
Nothing as good as what I told you.
Stealing somebody's footlocker, was that a... Oh, yeah.
The whole gamut of hiding things.
Where would you hide them?
It wasn't really a whole lot of places to hide them.
You'd usually hide them in somebody else's room.
You might, for instance, if I wanted to steal a sophomore's shoes, you know, to get in with the problem, I might hide them under the bed of the senior whose newborn was taken care of.
Did you all play hall hockey?
That I know in the 60s they would play it with the ball in the hallway and you would kick it through the door at the end of the hallway and it was kind of like kickball.
No, that must have been a new generation.
Tell me about the bull ring.
Where was it?
What was it?
Well, four infractions primarily involved with the military discipline.
or other things, you were given a penalty which involved walking, that we had to do it and walk it off in the bullring.
And an hour on the bullring, it was certainly a deal that had somebody watching and we'd walk the bullring to get these penalties off.
When did you do that?
Was there a specific time?
A lot of times it was Saturday afternoon.
In uniform?
In uniform.
In full uniform.
Where was it?
One of them was very close to where Abbelled Hall is.
just off that edge.
There's another one over I think near, right at the place where Keene is.
But after my freshman year, I managed to figure out a way not to be on the program.
What do you think the men in your outfit
thought about you as a sophomore?
What kind of a sophomore were you?
I was, I probably had a high ranking with freshmen and sophomores, because I was still a basketball player.
And so I didn't have time to harass them as much as others.
And also, having been out of school for two years,
I was a little bit more mature than the other sophomores.
And it sort of arrived at the conclusion that some of this was a bunch of bullshit, so to speak.
So I didn't harass the freshmen here as badly as the other sophomores.
I was more popular with the freshmen than some of the other sophomores.
However, the juniors and seniors ruled me pretty hard for not being tough enough on the freshmen.
What were the incentives for you to succeed at A&M?
The depression, family?
Tell me about those.
Well, my primary incentive, I suppose, was the fact that my parents expected all of their children to do well.
And I often think that a lot of the parents are really, in these days,
really messing up there by not having higher expectations for the children.
My mother particularly had high expectations for us and we ended up, all three of us, I think I ended up with six in one place.
And we were just expected to do well.
And I think that over most everything else.
All right.
And you and your brothers are first-generation college students.
Did either of your parents go to college?
No.
And you went to high school at Hallettsville?
Yes.
How many in your senior class?
32 of them.
It wasn't a great thing to be in the class of 32.
Do you remember anything about the retention rate in your freshman, sophomore years?
Well, when the grades came out, the first grades came out, I think it was about the third, third of the freshman year.
About how many would graduate in your outfit?
I'd say less than half.
Yeah, less than half.
Important question.
Who were some of the memorable teachers
counselors, advisors, staff members.
Tell me about as many of those as you can.
Well, Dr. Wolfram was great.
I thought he did a good job, particularly working with the student leaders.
Mr. Crawford was outstanding.
What did he do?
He taught mechanics.
Chemistry?
Chemistry.
Physics?
I'm just trying to think about it.
We had an outstanding lecture on chemistry.
I didn't get down to Stanford.
Well, I enjoyed physics, but I didn't get down to Stanford.
English, math?
I'm afraid I've forgotten most of them.
Were there some characters that you remember?
I can't remember either character.
Describe him, please.
Why was he Satch?
I think it's because of carrying that satchel.
Describe Dr. Walton, President Walton's personality and
Well, he really had an easy going personality.
You could say that he could get into a crowd and fit in anywhere he wanted to and the students liked T.O.
Hawkins.
Gilchrist, describe him please.
Gilchrist was a little scientist.
There again, he was a very well liked person.
And he really stood in behind his engineers.
And just like I was telling you, he was Colonel Watson.
He managed to get that thing straightened out without all the darn things that Colonel Watson brought.
In the Corps, were there some memorable Corps officials?
We mostly knew the people that were there, like Colonel Adcock was head of the engineers, and I thought he did a good job.
But later on, after he went to Lucian's and returned to train a rather easier maintenance company, Colonel Adcock found out I was in the States.
got what we assigned as Engineering Reckoning.
First thing you do is go back overseas and you're studying.
Instead of saving the engineer maintenance company, but at that time we were very anxious to do this.
I'm reciting this, you know, we were graduating early.
Not too early, but a few, two, three weeks early.
And all of the engineers went to San Houston
Fort Salem used to move and there wasn't a single one that wanted not to get his commission.
I remember very well, there was a classmate, E.E.
Bird, he called E-Square.
And I was appellate and he was E.E.
Bird's, so we were next each other.
They took, it was the very third physical examination, including a whole chest x-ray.
And I was called in and told that I had physical pain.
And I had evidence of having had some damage.
Of course.
Of course, I was begging robots to do it.
I said, well, I had no mystery of this.
I don't think it's that bad.
I don't say I could possibly be right.
And so one of the medical officers there took a look at my denture.
He said, this isn't as big as I am.
He said, his chest is 50% bigger than this.
And it turned out it was E squared.
And he busted out.
And I mean, it was absolutely devastating.
It wasn't like in .
We did not want to be busted out.
Now, this is the spring of 41.
What was your nickname?
They all call me this.
Just last?
You didn't have any?
Let's go to classroom behavior.
Oh, OK.
What were the expectations of class?
How did you all behave in class?
Did you go to class regularly?
Did you stay awake?
We behaved fairly well.
I think that was part of the effect of the military school.
They were disciplined.
The professors insisted.
Was the roll checked?
Absolutely.
And grades went home.
Did y'all even compute grade point ratios?
Y'all didn't talk about GPA, did you?
Yeah.
OK. Now, you came?
planning to major in engineering and you stayed with engineering the whole way looking back what were the most important courses that you took and why
A mechanics course, physics courses.
Of course, the English is really a high rating, but other than the English for economics, it all started very well.
And the little writing and public speaking we had.
Had you done slide rule in high school?
So that began.
Was there a cut?
I still have the slide rule right down here.
I don't know where it was.
Where was the, who taught you how to use the slide rule?
That was the portion, yeah.
OK. And typical engineer freshmen took that.
And how did you transport the slide rule from one place to another?
Where did you?
In the case, we hung it on the belt.
And all the, you can tell engineers that way, all the engineers.
All right, among you engineers, engineering was the prime major.
Was there any major on the campus that y'all looked down on, made fun of, teased about?
There were so few in it that they invested in liberal arts.
We didn't have a liberal arts group.
I don't think we even had a liberal arts college.
So that almost everybody was either in ag.
Or engineering.
What was the most, did any particular field of engineering have the largest enrollment?
Was there one that was most popular?
Probably civil and mechanical.
And we had electrical, chemical.
Let's talk about the library.
Did you all call it Cushing or just Cushing Library or just the library?
And was it possible to go over there and find a corner to snooze and to sleep in?
You can try it, but it's the sophomore who regularly leaves the library.
And did you all...
Since I had a face strike on freshman year, we've had sophomores from one of the infantry companies, I'll tell you a couple of them, he'd come to sleep and then he'd report it to my sophomore.
And that's, that's bad.
Typically, a network of
The sophomore was working in the mess hall.
And they had a mess hall.
They had punished him by taking a knife, taking a flat-feathered knife and hitting it real rapidly in the palm of your hand.
And it just really started smarting.
Did that have a name doing that?
See, I haven't heard that one before.
Would that happen when you got caught?
Right then?
Back to the library.
How much time did you spend in the library?
Very little.
Very little research.
And your academic load per semester was normally what?
Eighteen.
And you graduated in what?
Four years.
I wouldn't have thought of anything else, my gosh.
You spend money to do an extra semester.
Here's the thought.
All right, the YMCA.
What role did it play in the campus?
Well, we had the other practitioners.
a Lutheran group for me Sunday evening on the second floor of the YMCA.
And so were lots of other groups.
Describe, let's go back, you said your Lutheran group.
Mention what that was.
Well, just a group of Lutheran affiliated students.
Were there similar groups for other denominations?
Who was the key leader?
Was there an advisor?
There was, I think, one of the local pastors.
Okay.
Who headed the YMCA then?
Was it Mr. Cashin?
Yeah, it was.
Red Cashin's dad?
Yeah, his dad, that's right.
Sure was.
And let's see, what else happened in the YD?
Well, that was a place where if someone was going to come to the campus, you might tell them that you would meet them at the Y.
But it was a central meeting place.
And there was, you see the drill field was just dying across from the Y.
And there was a, at that time there was a silver moon for Campbell's Park in the room.
driveways and so forth.
There weren't that many cars.
This was my senior year.
We had one car.
It was an old Model A Ford Roadster with a rubber seat.
